# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: circuit-breaker-pattern
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] The **Circuit Breaker** is a design pattern commonly used in software development to improve system resilience and fault tolerance.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] Circuit breaker pattern can prevent cascading failures particularly in distributed systems.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] In distributed systems, the Circuit Breaker pattern can be used to monitor service health and can detect failures dynamically.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] Unlike timeout-based methods, which can lead to delayed error responses or the premature failure of healthy requests, the Circuit Breaker pattern can proactively identify unresponsive services and can prevent repeated attempts.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] This approach can enhance the user experience.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] The circuit breaker pattern can be used in conjunction with other patterns, such as retry, fallback, and timeout, to enhance fault tolerance in systems.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] According to Marc Brooker, circuit breakers can misinterpret a partial failure as total system failure and inadvertently bring down the entire system.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] In particular, sharded systems and cell-based architectures are vulnerable to this issue.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] A workaround is that the server indicates to the client which specific part is overloaded and the client uses a corresponding mini circuit breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] However, this workaround can be complex and expensive.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] When everything is normal, the circuit breakers remain *closed*, and all the requests pass through to the services.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] If the number of failures increases beyond the threshold, the circuit breaker trips and goes into an *open* state.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] In this state circuit breaker returns an error immediately without even invoking the services.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] The Circuit breakers move into the *half-open* state after a timeout period elapses.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] Usually, it will have a monitoring system where the timeout will be specified.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] In this state, the circuit breaker allows a limited number of requests from the service to pass through and invoke the operation.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] If the requests are successful, then the circuit breaker will go to the *closed* state.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/circuit-breaker-design-pattern] However, if the requests continue to fail, then it goes back to *open* state.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] The term "failover", although probably in use by engineers much earlier, can be found in a 1962 declassified NASA report.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] The term "switchover" can be found in the 1950s when describing '"Hot" and "Cold" Standby Systems', with the current meaning of immediate switchover to a running system (hot) and delayed switchover to a system that needs starting (cold).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] A conference proceedings from 1957 describes computer systems with both Emergency Switchover (i.e., failover) and Scheduled Failover (for maintenance).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] Systems designers usually provide failover capability in servers, systems or networks requiring high availability and a high degree of reliability.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] At the server level, failover automation usually sends a heartbeat between two servers, either through the network or through a separate connection (for example, RS-232).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] In the most common design, as long as a regular "pulse" or heartbeat continues between the main server and the second server, the second server will not bring its systems online; however, a few systems actively use all servers and can failover their work to remaining servers after a failure.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] There may also be a third "spare parts" server that has running spare components for "hot" switching to prevent downtime.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] The second server takes over the work of the first as soon as it detects an alteration in the heartbeat of the first machine.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] Some systems have the ability to send a notification of failover.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] Certain systems, intentionally, do not fail over entirely automatically, but require human intervention.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] This "automated with manual approval" configuration runs automatically once a human has approved the failover.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] The use of virtualization software has allowed failover practices to become less reliant on physical hardware through the process referred to as migration in which a running virtual machine is moved from one physical host to another, with little or no disruption in service.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] Failover and failback technology are also regularly used in the Microsoft SQL Server database, in which SQL Server Failover Cluster Instance (FCI) is installed and configured on top of the Windows Server Failover Cluster (WSFC).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] The SQL Server groups and resources running on WSFC can be manually failed over to the second node for any planned maintenance on the first node or automatically fail over to the second node in case of any issues on the first node.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/failover] In the same way, a failback operation can be performed to the first node once the issue is resolved or maintenance is done on it.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/resilience-network] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/timeout-computing] Timeouts allow for more efficient usage of limited resources without requiring additional interaction from the agent interested in the goods that cause the consumption of these resources.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/timeout-computing] The basic idea is that in situations where a system must wait for something to happen, rather than waiting indefinitely, the waiting will be aborted after the timeout period has elapsed.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/timeout-computing] This is based on the assumption that further waiting is useless, and some other action is necessary.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/timeout-computing] Balancing timeout values in distributed systems and microservices can be tricky: short timeout values can fail healthy requests prematurely, leading to complex workarounds, while long timeout values can result in slow error responses and poor user experiences.
[src:circuit-breaker-pattern/timeout-computing] The circuit breaker design pattern can be a better alternative, as it can monitor service health, detect failures dynamically and faster, and improve the user experience.
